    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-11-10T18:48:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-11-10T18:48:00-05:00" n="310"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d310">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">320/11–852: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">United States Mission at the United Nations</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d310fn1">This telegram was drafted by
                            <persName>Brown</persName> of <gloss target="#t_UNP1">UNP</gloss> and
                        cleared by <persName corresp="#p_WDW1">Wainhouse</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA1">Johnson</persName>, and with <persName
                            corresp="#p_HJD1">Hickerson</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-11-10T18:48:00-05:00"
                            >November 10, 1952—6:48 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Gadel1">Gadel</gloss> 48. Re Korea, <gloss target="#t_Delga1"
                        >Delga</gloss> 151, <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 149.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d310fn2">Both dated Nov. 8, <ref target="#pg_588">pp. 588</ref> and
                            <ref target="#pg_585">585</ref>, respectively.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Confirming <persName corresp="#p_GEA1">Gross</persName>–<persName
                            corresp="#p_HJD1">Hickerson</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_JUA1"
                            >Johnson</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_WDW1"
                            >Wainhouse</persName>–<persName corresp="#p_HL1">Henkin</persName>
                        <gloss target="#t_telecon1">telecon</gloss>, fol are Dept’s comments on
                        draft res <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 151: <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Re para 2, insert words “for Korea” after words “armistice
                                agreement”.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Re para 2B, Dept’s strong preference is for establishment
                                impartial comm to which <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> wld name
                                membs. US cld accept any state outside Sov bloc. However, if
                                necessary to obtain Ind agreement, US wld accept provision for
                                impartial comm leaving actual membership to negots at Panmunjom. If
                                Inds maintain that Chi Commies will accept only membs Neutral
                                Nations Supervisory Body (Sweden, Switzerland, Poland, Czecho), plus
                                “umpire”, US wld insist either that <gloss target="#t_GA1"
                                    >GA</gloss> appoint in advance “umpire” envisaged by Inds, or
                                that, if 4 membs unable agree upon umpire at first mtg, <gloss
                                    target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> wld name “umpire” or possibly wld
                                delegate responsibility to appropriate internatl official such as
                                Pres <gloss target="#t_ICJ1">ICJ</gloss>. Preference in latter
                                connection, however, wld be for <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>
                                designate umpire in advance, his appointment to become effective if
                                4 states unable agree on “umpire” at first mtg. In discussing above
                                with Inds, <gloss target="#t_Gadel1">GADel</gloss> shld stress
                                willingness accept impartial comm of any 3 states outside Commie
                                bloc, membs of UN or otherwise; if Inds indicate Commies wld not
                                accept such comm, US wld agree to 4 “neutral” states with <gloss
                                    target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss> naming umpire, as indicated
                                above.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Re para 2B(1). Substitute word “demilitarized” for
                                “neutral”.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Re para 2B(3). Insert word “humanitarian” before word
                                “principles”.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Fol are Dept’s tentative reactions to list of points developed by
                            <persName corresp="#p_MVKK1">Menon</persName> (<gloss target="#t_Delga1"
                            >Delga</gloss> 149): <list>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">a</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Paras 1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 9, 10 acceptable.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">b</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Paras 2 and 8 raise problem composition repatriation comm on which
                                Dept views already indicated in para 1<hi rend="italic">b</hi>
                                above.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">c</hi>.</label>
                            <item>Dept considers para 7 unhappily worded and too detailed. Strongly
                                prefer formulation para 1 <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss>
                                151.</item>
                            <label>
                                <hi rend="italic">d</hi>.</label>
                            <item>US cld not accept para 11. However, we can accept formulation on
                                polit conf set forth <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 151 or
                                provision according which <gloss target="#t_GA1">GA</gloss>
                                “approves” to holding of polit conf provided for in para 60 draft
                                armis agreement as indicated <gloss target="#t_Gadel1">Gadel</gloss>
                                    41.<note n="3" xml:id="d310fn3">In <gloss target="#t_Gadel1"
                                        >Gadel</gloss> 41, dated Nov. 7, 1952, the Department of
                                    State gave its preliminary comments on the list of elements
                                    basic to the U.S. position on Korea in the General Assembly as
                                    set out in <gloss target="#t_Delga1">Delga</gloss> 133, dated
                                    Nov. 6, <ref target="#pg_579">p. 579</ref>, including acceptance
                                    of a political conference approved by the General Assembly, if
                                    the Secretary of State concurred (320/11–652).</note>
                            </item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BDKE1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bruce</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
